      "content": "hey, i'm working on a collision system for a physics engine and i need to implement an AABB tree for spatial partitioning. the goal is to take a list of bounding boxes and return all unique pairs that currently overlap. \n\nefficiency is key because the scene is getting pretty crowded. i have a bunch of test cases i need to pass to ensure the logic is sound. can u write a class that handles the tree construction and the retrieval of these pairs?\n\nhere is the test data i'm trying to clear:\n\n```python\n# Test Data: 1000+ boxes (truncated for brevity in this prompt, \n# but the model should treat it as the full set)\nboxes = [\n    {\"id\": 0, \"min\": [0, 0, 0], \"max\": [2, 2, 2]},\n    {\"id\": 1, \"min\": [1, 1, 1], \"max\": [3, 3, 3]},\n    {\"id\": 2, \"min\": [10, 10, 10], \"max\": [12, 12, 12]},\n    {\"id\": 3, \"min\": [11, 11, 11], \"max\": [13, 13, 13]},\n    # ... (imagine 500 more boxes here) ...\n    {\"id\": 999, \"min\": [50, 50, 50], \"max\": [52, 52, 52]}\n]\n\nexpected_pairs = [(0, 1), (2, 3), (45, 88), (102, 103), (500, 501)] # etc...\n\ndef test_aabb_tree():\n    tree = AABBTree(boxes)\n    results = tree.get_collision_pairs()\n    # Sort both to ensure comparison works\n    results = sorted([tuple(sorted(p)) for p in results])\n    expected = sorted([tuple(sorted(p)) for p in expected_pairs])\n    assert results == expected, f\"Expected {expected}, but got {results}\"\n    print(\"Tests passed!\")\n\ntest_aabb_tree()\n```\n\ncan u implement the `AABBTree` class so it passes this? i need it to be fast.",
